column9: Egyptian abode of the blessed dead.
Melanesian afterworld where life is easier than on Earth.
New Guinea goddess of creation and knowledge who teaches people how to live correctly.
Planet from the Dune series; IV Anbus, home of Tibana, an apologist for Socratic Christianity.
Name of a mountain range from Middle-earth, the fictional setting in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Archipelago corresponding to the mythical island of Antilia, once thought to lie midway between Europe and the Americas.
Mythological river in the Aztec Underworld.
Armenian god famous for his beauty, also known as a resurrected god who dies and is reborn periodically.
Planet from the Dune series; home of the Fremen, a group of fictional people whose culture revolves around preservation and conservation of water, which is a rare commodity on the planet.
Daughter of Elrond; character from Middle-earth, the fictional setting in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Greek Titanis goddess of the morning wind.
Mythical land from which the Aztecs believed they migrated.
Bayta Darell, fictional character in Isaac Asimov's Foundation Series, wife of the Trader Tran Darell and grandmother of famous author Arcadia “Arcady” Darell.
Celtic/Irish goddess of water, education, and knowledge. Anyone who drinks the water from her well will become wise.
Malay afterworld reached by a flower-lined bridge.
An enchanted island in Shakespeare’s Tempest.
Hobbit, the main character in ‘The Hobbit’ novel; he traveled across Middle-earth, the fictional setting in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Boicua; Island in Arawak (Bahamas) legend said to contain the fountain of youth.
Greek god of the north wind.
Baralku; In Yolngu culture (Arnhem Land, Australia), the island of the dead and the place where the Djanggawul, the three creator siblings, originated.
A rocky island in Russian folk tales located on the south shore of the Baltic Sea.
Planet from the Dune series; a cold planet, known for its lustrous Soostones, used as a “punishment planet” by the Bene Gesserit.
Planet from the Dune series; the original home of the House Atriedes, a fictional noble family.
Chinese Buddhist paradise where those who attain salvation will live in unalloyed happiness.
Planet from the Dune series, known for its musical instruments.
Planet from the Dune series; site of Battle of Corrin.
Sumerian garden of paradise, primeval land of bliss.
Name of a mountain from Middle-earth, the fictional setting in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Name of a mountain from Middle-earth, the fictional setting  in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Planet from the Dune series; useful for its agricultural contributions to the Imperium.
Name of a mountain range from Middle-earth, the fictional setting in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Norse goddess of healing and peace.
In Norse mythology, twelve poisonous ice-cold rivers.
Greek goddess of happiness and hope.
Name of a mountain from Middle-earth, the fictional setting  in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Greek personification of the east wind.
Wise man of nobility; character from Middle-earth, the fictional setting in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
In Norse mythology, magnificent mansion of Frigga, to which she invited all married couples who had led virtuous lives on Earth to enjoy each other's company forever.
Norse god, the wisest and most eloquent of the Aesir.
Planet from the Dune series; the name for the planet Giedi Prime after the fall of House Harkonnen.
Planet from the Dune series; third planet of Niushe, noted for its hedonistic culture.
Wizard, leader of the Fellowship of the Ring; character from Middle-earth, the fictional setting fantasy novels by J. R. R. Tolkien.
Hindu god of good fortune and wisdom.
Planet from the Dune series; with a village named London.
Iranian paradise where the souls of faithful men dwell.
Planet from the Dune series; Giedi Prime is the homeworld of  House Harkonnen.
Planet from the Dune series; home of House Ginaz.
Name of a mountain from Middle-earth, the fictional setting in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Planet from the Dune series; where Duncan Idaho first blooded his sword.
Taino Indian (Antilles) sea goddess who taught the use of amulets.
Planet from the Dune series; a jewel planet known for its quality quartz, and which is mined out in the time of Shaddam I.
Son of Haldir, a ruler of the fictional Folk of Haleth; character from Middle-earth, the fictional setting in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Bella Coola (northwestern USA and western Canada) goddess of education, knowledge, and magic. She manifested as a shaman so she could teach the people.
Salvor Hardin, fictional character in Isaac Asimov's Foundation Series, first Mayor of the planet Terminus.
Planet from Dune series; sixth stop in the Zensunni migration.
One of the seven gods of happiness in Japanese Buddhism. He is the god of contentment, good fortune, cheerfulness, and he is always smiling.
One of the seven gods of happiness in Japanese Buddhism. He is the god of contentment, good fortune, and cheerfulness, and he is always smiling.
The river that flows at the gates of the netherworld in Mesopotamian mythology.
Legendary island in the marshes of southern Iraq.
Name of a mountain from Middle-earth, the fictional setting  in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Planet from the Dune series; once controlled by the Spacing Guild, taken over by the Honored Matres as a stronghold for their leader.
Planet from the Dune series; the capital of the Imperium.
NW Australian rainbow serpent, bringer of rain.
Lake on the border between Rwanda and The Democratic Republic of the Congo.
Fabulous sea monster in the Norwegian seas, said to be a mile   and a half in circumference and to cause a whirlpool when it dives.
Crocylea; Mythological Greek island in the Ionian Sea, near Ithaca.
Planet from the Dune series; captured by the Honored Matres.
Lakota and Oglala (South Dakota, USA) god of wisdom.
Intermittent lake on the border of India and Pakistan.
Planet from the Dune series; a center for Bene Gesserit education, also where Miles Teg is trained as a Mentat.
Planet from the Dune series; where Glossu Rabban, the nephew of Baron Harkonnen, is a Count.
Persian goddess of beauty and chastity.
Planet from the Dune series; where Miles Teg retires, also the home planet of his Bene Gesserit mother, Lady Janet Roxbrough.
One of the sirens in Greek mythology.
Legendary island in the northeastern region of the Atlantic Ocean.
Name of a mountain from Middle-earth, the fictional setting in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Oasis of happiness in the African desert, from an Italian legend.
Name of a mountain from Middle-earth, the fictional setting  in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Name of a mountain range from Middle-earth, the fictional setting  in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Name of a mountain range from Middle-earth, the fictional setting  in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Indian goddess of beauty and magic.
Chumash (California, USA) ancestor shaman and goddess of magic, education, knowledge, health and healing.
Name of three massive peaks, the Mountains of Moria, at the midpoint of the Misty Mountains range from Middle-earth, the fictional setting in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Planet from the Dune series; place where the son of a female supplicant to Alia Atreides was killed.
Lake in Zambia and Democratic Republic of the Congo.
Greek nymph, a minor deity, nurse of the god Dionysus, who instructed him in the Mysteries.
Planet from the Dune series; where the son of Farok lost his eyes.
Lake in Northern Ireland, United Kingdom.
Second queen of Doriath, a fictional realm of Grey Elves; character from Middle-earth, the fictional setting in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Planet from the Dune series; planet captured by the Honored Matres.
Greek god of the south or southwest wind.
Puerto Rican goddess of happiness and weather.
Lake on the border of Macedonia and Albania.
Aztec god of good cheer and lord of banquets.
Lake on the border between Canada and the United States.
Planet from the Dune series; home to a Bene Gesserit Keep, attacked by the Honored Matres.
Aymara (Peru, Bolivia) goddess of the moon, education and knowledge.
Mythological Chinese mountain island where immortals lived.
Lithuanian supreme god, ruler of rain, thunder, and lightning.
In Greek mythology the “wandering rocks”, between which the sea was mercilessly violent. Only Argo was said to have successfully passed the rocks.
Slavic god of New Year's happiness.
East Slavic god of matrimonial happiness.
Planet from the Dune series; third planet of Epsilon Alangue, considered by many Zensunni Wanderers as their planet of origin.
Lake in the Republic of Macedonia, Albania, and Greece.
Sound in state of Washington, USA.
Māori (New Zealand) supernatural being, the father of sharks and lizards. Son of the sea god Tangaroa.
Kukunor, Tso Ngonpo; lake in China.
Legendary city in the American Southwest; site of a fabulous treasure sought by Coronado and other explorers.
Name of a mountain from Middle-earth, the fictional setting in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Planet from the Dune series; fourth planet of Eridani A, supreme in machine culture, noted for miniaturization.
Beautiful Māori goddess, wife of Māui.
Planet from the Dune series; the planet on which the younger brother of Miles Teg was poisoned.
Planet from the Dune series; the source planet for the Bene Gesserit's original poison drug, or, the "Water of Life", and the origin of the Bene Gesserit order itself.
Island in Atlantic Ocean (15th Century maps) on verge of the unknown, near Antilla and St. Brandan.
Planet from the Dune series; Salusa Secundus, used as the Imperial Prison Planet.
Greek island also known as Thira.
Hari Seldon, the fictional, intellectual hero of Isaac Asimov's Foundation Series, First Minister of the Galactic Empire.
Egyptian goddess of knowledge, writing, education, and reptiles.
Japanese ideal realm of aloofness and serenity, freedom from wordly cares and death.
Tibetan mythical land of eternal youth.
Planet from the Dune series, home to the useful plant akarso.
Kachin (N. Burma) wise spirit who dwells in the sky and gives wisdom to his worshippers.
Melanesian (New Ireland Island, Papua New Guinea) god of wisdom.
Name of a mountain from Middle-earth, the fictional setting  in fantasy novels by J.R.R. Tolkien.
Planet from the Dune series; home world of the Bene Tleilax.
Aztec paradise where crops never fade.
Island in the British Virgin Islands.
Golan Trevize, fictional character in Isaac Asimov's Foundation Series, councilman of the planet Terminus.
Hopi name for Mount Taylor (New Mexico, US), as a sacred  mountain.
Chinese goddess of happiness, joy, and water.
Planet from the Dune series; “sanctuary planet” for defeated houses of the Imperium.
In Norse mythology, a broad river of the ice-cold poisonous Elivagar system.
Indonesian first woman, known for her great beauty.
An imaginary country in Coleridge's "Kubla Khan."
Australian spirit land filled with game and clean water for good souls.
Greek personification of the gentle west wind.
